	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every statistic is a real person in a white coat — maybe you. The patient you couldn't save who still visits you at 3 a.m. The charting that follows you home. The moral injury of knowing the right care and being unable to give it. The quiet detachment you've learned to wear so you can function. The unspoken expectation that you, of all people, must never break.</p><p>None of this means something is wrong with you. It means you are a human being doing one of the most sacred and impossible jobs there is — carrying responsibility no person was built to carry alone. There is a Father who sees the real you underneath the coat, and He has something to say about who you actually are.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `Mayo Clinic Proceedings — Physician Burnout and Professional Satisfaction (2023 study)`, url: `https://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196(23)00430-5/fulltext` },
		{ label: `Medscape — Physician Burnout & Depression Report`, url: `https://www.medscape.com/slideshow/2024-lifestyle-burnout-6016865` },
		{ label: `National Academy of Medicine — Clinician Well-Being and Resilience`, url: `https://nam.edu/initiatives/clinician-resilience-and-well-being/` },
	]}
	aFatherHeading={`A Father for doctors`}
	aFatherBodyHtml={`<p>Here's what almost no one tells a physician: the answer to the burnout isn't more resilience, a better work-life balance hack, or finally becoming the doctor who never makes a mistake. The answer is a <strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">Father</strong> — a perfect, holy Father who already loves you, today, before a single outcome.</p><p>You were not made to be God. You were made to be His child. You hold others' lives in your hands, and that is a holy calling — but you were never meant to bear it as if everything depended on you alone. The One who made you carries the One who carries everyone. He doesn't grade you by your mortality rates or your hours logged. He calls you His beloved — not the heroic you, not the unbreakable you, but <em>you</em>, the tired one underneath the coat.</p><p>So before you're a physician, a surgeon, the strong one everyone leans on — you are His. Your heavenly Father wants to be the rest beneath your work, the steady voice that says: I see you, I'm proud of you, you can lay it down with Me — and there is nothing you could do to make Me love you more, or less.</p>`}
