	voicesHeading={`The Father's heart, in their words`}
	voicesIntroHtml={`You hold others' lives in your hands — but you were never meant to be God. The truth beneath every verse here, that He is before anything else a Father, is the one these voices gave their lives to:`}
	voices={[
		{ quote: `There is heaven in the depth of that word — Father.`, name: `Charles Spurgeon`, role: `the “Prince of Preachers”`, photo: `https://cdn.sanity.io/images/rusi1hyi/production/e48a128da123135241be9c95cf35b37498d94ea5-500x617.jpg` },
		{ quote: `Answered prayer is the interchange of love between the Father and His child.`, name: `Andrew Murray`, role: `who taught a generation to live as the Father's children`, photo: `https://cdn.sanity.io/images/rusi1hyi/production/133bc45cfa954cf1ae99b7afac5954eca764ed70-500x830.jpg` },
		{ quote: `The hardest, gladdest thing in the world is, to cry Father! from a full heart.`, name: `George MacDonald`, role: `who taught that the Fatherhood of God is the heart of the gospel`, photo: `https://cdn.sanity.io/images/rusi1hyi/production/35e71c2610893383d20b60883aa0b1d4d4664cbc-500x726.jpg` },
	]}
	voicesCreditHtml={`Photos via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Wikimedia Commons</a> &mdash; Charles Spurgeon, Andrew Murray, and George MacDonald (all public domain).`}
	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>You might not feel different the first time you read it after a brutal day. That's okay. The Father's love isn't a surge of adrenaline — it's a foundation, and foundations get built quietly, one day at a time. Every verse you take in is your Father planting rest in you that the next shift can't uproot.</p><p class="mt-4" style="color: var(--color-ink);">"My word… will not return to me empty, but will accomplish that which I purpose." <span style="color: var(--color-muted);">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What your Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>"I know the weight you carry. I see the patient you couldn't save, the chart that follows you home, the strength you fake so no one worries. And I want you to hear Me over all of it: you are Mine, and you don't have to be Me. I am the One who carries everyone — including the One who carries them through you.</p><p>You were never meant to hold life and death alone. Come to Me when you're weary and I will give you rest — real rest, the kind your days off can't reach. Practice from My peace, not from the fear that everything depends on you. Lay the impossible weight down here. I made you on purpose, I am proud of you, and I love you the same on your worst day as your best. You don't have to be the savior. I already am. Just come, and let Me carry you."</p>`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for doctors`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we thank You and praise You for these doctors — every physician carrying more than anyone sees. Let them hear Your whisper above the alarms and the exhaustion — the pressure to be perfect, the grief they have no time to feel, the lie that they have to be the strong one alone. Let them encounter Your love — not as one more demand, but as a Father's delight — and know they are Your beloved, apart from any outcome or hour logged.</p><p>Give them rest, Father — the soul-deep rest only You can give — and renew the strength their work drains away. Protect them from burnout, from moral injury, from emotional numbness, and from despair; guard their hearts and minds, and keep watch over them in the long nights when they feel they cannot go on. Provide for them and their families, and steady their hands and their judgment.</p><p>Give them clarity in the moments medicine cannot answer, and the humility to lean on You rather than on their own understanding. Let them know there is no condemnation in You, that Your grace is enough where they feel weakest, and that underneath them are Your everlasting arms. Let them know You, their Father, as the rest beneath all their work. And may they wake each day knowing they were carried first, before they ever carried anyone else.</p><p>In Jesus' name, amen.</p>`}
