	keepReadingHtml={`Start with the <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">whole Bible free online with audio</a>, learn <a href="/the-fathers-heart-bible/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">why the Father's Heart Bible™ exists</a>, or get oriented with our <a href="/guides/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Bible reading guides</a> — including <a href="/guides/how-to-pray/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">how to pray</a> and <a href="/verses/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">verses by topic</a>. Or meet the Father in another season with the rest of the <a href="/bible-for/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">A Father For series</a>.`}
	faqs={[
		{ question: `What are good Bible verses for doctors?`, answer: `Matthew 11:28-30 (come to Me and I will give you rest), Psalm 121 (He who keeps you will not slumber), Isaiah 40:28-31 (He gives strength to the weary), 2 Corinthians 12:9 (My grace is sufficient, My power is perfect in weakness), Psalm 46:1 (an ever-present help in trouble), Isaiah 41:10 (I will uphold you), and Deuteronomy 33:27 (underneath are the everlasting arms) all speak straight to the weight physicians carry. Read and hear them free in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about burnout and exhaustion?`, answer: `Scripture takes your exhaustion seriously. Matthew 11:28-30 is Jesus' direct invitation to the weary and weighed down: come to Me and I will give you rest. Isaiah 40:28-31 promises that those who wait on God renew their strength and run without growing weary. The Father's Heart Bible™ reveals God as a Father you can actually bring your burnout to — read those passages free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Is there scripture for physicians carrying the weight of life and death?`, answer: `Yes. You hold others' lives in your hands, but Scripture is clear you were never meant to be God. Psalm 46:1 calls Him an ever-present help in trouble, Proverbs 3:5-6 invites you to lean on Him rather than your own understanding, and Deuteronomy 33:27 promises His everlasting arms underneath you. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet the Father who carries the One who carries everyone — read it free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about feeling weak or like a failure?`, answer: `It reframes weakness entirely. 2 Corinthians 12:9 says God's grace is enough and His power is made perfect in weakness — so the place you feel you're failing is the very place He shows up. Isaiah 41:10 promises He will strengthen and uphold you. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet God as a Father who loves you the same on your worst day as your best. Read these free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Is there a free Bible with audio for doctors and healthcare workers?`, answer: `Yes. The Father's Heart Bible™ is free to read and listen to online — no account, no purchase, no app. Open fathersheartbible.com/read on your phone and read or hear any book — perfect for listening between rounds, on the commute home, or in the quiet after a hard shift.` },
		{ question: `What makes the Father's Heart Bible™ different for doctors?`, answer: `It's the first English translation to reveal God as Father wherever Scripture reveals Him as Father — so instead of one more authority telling you to perform, you meet the One who already delights in you. For a physician under crushing responsibility, that reframes everything: you come to the Bible as a loved child first, carried by the Father, not as the savior you feel you have to be.` },
		{ question: `How can a busy doctor start reading the Bible?`, answer: `Start small and start free. Open fathersheartbible.com/read, pick a Psalm or a short passage, and listen to the audio while you drive or decompress. Try a verse a day — Matthew 11, Psalm 121, or Isaiah 40 are great places to begin. Our how-to-pray guide and verses-by-topic pages can help you find words for whatever the day has left you carrying.` },
	]}
